At 3:58, this video has lost its credibility as did the reviewer. This shot made him doubt his conclusion about the Pixel 4? No doubt the Pixel took the best shot. This is a portrait type of a photograph obviously with the person as the foreground, and the Pixel produced the most pleasing picture of the subject. The background is not the focus here. What detail? Look at her hairline in the iPhone's picture. You could clearly see the strands of her hair in the Pixel"s photo.

What bugs me is these "reviewers" are also called "influencers" who can dramatically sway consumers to a certain direction. And with that, I hold them to a higher standard to call a spade a spade. I wouldn't trust this guy with my tech purchasing decisions.

snippet.textDisplay: I agree with you about the huawei being the most overrated cameras. Clearly the reviews of huawei cameras the last two years have been paid/nudged by huawei. snippet.textDisplay:
Still waiting for a phone with a good camera, these aren't it.
Generally the photos were mediocre at best. However, the one that stood out as truly horrendous was the diner image of the model. The iPhone shots were literal garbage. Who cares if the background highlights are a little blown in the pixel shot, if the main subject looks like someone sculpted a face into a turd in the iPhone image.

I will stick to my decade old real camera for anytime I want a serious photo, and continue to use the terrible phone camera for nothing more than memories or reference shots.

snippet.textDisplay: To me all stills of Pixel 4 looked better, at least after Youtube's processing and on my old IPS display. But I also agree with some of the comments: a "gold standard" from a professional DSLR of the same shot would make differences in actual captured details a lot easier to tell, and in the end - that's all that matters. You can always adjust captures in post, but if the camera doesn't capture enough data in the first place, there's nothing you can do.
